06019nam a22009855i 9783110666199DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106661997 a10.1515/97831106661992doi  a(DE-B1597)532572  a(OCoLC)1191864495  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aDS432.H6bR45 2020 7aREL0290002bisacsh04a305.8959/52231 aReichel, Eva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ho: Living in a World of Plenty :bOf Social Cohesion and Ritual Friendship on the Chota Nagpur Plateau, India /cEva Reichel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XVIII, 394 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Society ,x1437-5370 ;v8400tFrontmatter -- tAbstract -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAnnotations -- tPrologue -- t1 Introduction: Living in a world of plenty -- t2 The Chota Nagpur Plateau: terrain and people -- t3 Living in a world of relations: of Ho social categories -- t4 Ho accounts of social cohesion in history, myth, and the present -- t5 Relatedness across tribal boundaries: the Ho and their clients -- t6 The saki relation as ritual friendship -- t7 Two portraits as conclusion -- tAppendices -- tGlossary I: Notes on Ho history -- tGlossary II: Ho terms -- tLists of Plates, Figures, and Maps -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book is set in the anthropologically much-neglected multi-ethnic interior of Highland Middle India. It is the result of fieldwork done over a period of more than a decade among the Ho, an indigenous community of approximately one million people, who have shared cultural norms and the space of the hilly region of the Chota Nagpur Plateau with other aboriginal (adivasi) and artisan communities for ages. The book explores the structured tapestry of Ho people’s relations and interrelatedness within their culture-specific sociocosmic universe ensuring their social reproduction in the present and affording them the means for and the awareness of living in a world of plenty. This world of abundance – with the Ho as its conceptual centre – includes the Ho’s dead, their complex spirit world and supreme deity, and their tribal and nontribal fellow humans, and it manifests itself in manifold facets of their lives: socially, ritually, economically, and linguistically. "This is an important piece of work. The ethnographic details in it are invaluable. The fieldwork is superb. What comes across so magnificently is that unique quality of the author's human and emotional contact and shared understanding with the people." MICHAEL YORKE: University College, London; Upside Films  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAnthropology of religionzIndiazChota Nāgpur. 0aEthnologyzIndiazChota Nāgpur. 0aHo (Indic people). 0aIndigenous peopleszIndiazChota Nāgpur. 0aInterpersonal relationszIndiazChota Nāgpur. 0aSocial integrationzIndiazChota Nāgpur. 4aAdivasi. 4aFeldforschung. 4aRiten. 4aSociologie. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh  aAdivasi (first settlers).  asaki (ritual friend).  aspirit world.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt